{"name": "pytimeparse", "metadata": {"name": "pytimeparse", "version": "1.1.8", "classifiers": ["Development Status :: 4 - Beta", "Intended Audience :: Developers", "License :: OSI Approved :: MIT License", "Natural Language :: English", "Programming Language :: Python :: 2", "Programming Language :: Python :: 2.7", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3.2", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3.3", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3.4", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3.5", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3.6", "Topic :: Text Processing"], "home_page": "https://github.com/wroberts/pytimeparse", "license": "License :: OSI Approved :: MIT License", "documentation_url": null, "dependencies": [], "summary": "Time expression parser", "upload_time": 1526665241}, "documentation": ["# pytimeparse: time expression parser\n\n```{image} https://travis-ci.org/wroberts/pytimeparse.svg?branch=master\n:alt: Travis CI build status\n:target: https://travis-ci.org/wroberts/pytimeparse\n```\n\n```{image} https://coveralls.io/repos/wroberts/pytimeparse/badge.svg\n:alt: Test code coverage\n:target: https://coveralls.io/r/wroberts/pytimeparse\n```\n\n```{image} https://img.shields.io/pypi/v/pytimeparse.svg\n:alt: Latest Version\n:target: https://pypi.python.org/pypi/pytimeparse/\n```\n\nCopyright (c) 2014 Will Roberts \\<<mailto:wildwilhelm@gmail.com>>\n\nLicensed under the MIT License (see source file `timeparse.py` for\ndetails).\n\nA small Python library to parse various kinds of time expressions,\ninspired by\n[this StackOverflow question](http://stackoverflow.com/questions/4628122/how-to-construct-a-timedelta-object-from-a-simple-string).\n\nThe single function `pytimeparse.timeparse.timeparse` defined in the\nlibrary (also available as `pytimeparse.parse`) parses time\nexpressions like the following:\n\n- `32m`\n- `2h32m`\n- `3d2h32m`\n- `1w3d2h32m`\n- `1w 3d 2h 32m`\n- `1 w 3 d 2 h 32 m`\n- `4:13`\n- `4:13:02`\n- `4:13:02.266`\n- `2:04:13:02.266`\n- `2 days,  4:13:02` (`uptime` format)\n- `2 days,  4:13:02.266`\n- `5hr34m56s`\n- `5 hours, 34 minutes, 56 seconds`\n- `5 hrs, 34 mins, 56 secs`\n- `2 days, 5 hours, 34 minutes, 56 seconds`\n- `1.2 m`\n- `1.2 min`\n- `1.2 mins`\n- `1.2 minute`\n- `1.2 minutes`\n- `172 hours`\n- `172 hr`\n- `172 h`\n- `172 hrs`\n- `172 hour`\n- `1.24 days`\n- `5 d`\n- `5 day`\n- `5 days`\n- `5.6 wk`\n- `5.6 week`\n- `5.6 weeks`\n\nIt returns the time as a number of seconds (an integer value if\npossible, otherwise a floating-point number):\n\n```\n>>> from pytimeparse import parse\n>>> parse('1.2 minutes')\n72\n```\n\nA number of seconds can be converted back into a string using the\n`datetime` module in the standard library, as noted in\n[this other StackOverflow question](http://stackoverflow.com/questions/538666/python-format-timedelta-to-string):\n\n```\n>>> from pytimeparse import parse\n>>> import datetime\n>>> parse('1 day, 14:20:16')\n138016\n>>> str(datetime.timedelta(seconds=138016))\n'1 day, 14:20:16'\n```\n\n## Future work\n\n1. Give the user more flexibility over which characters to use as\n   separators between fields in a time expression (e.g., `+` might\n   be useful).\n2. Internationalisation?\n3. Wow, <https://github.com/bear/parsedatetime> .\n"], "modules": [{"name": "pytimeparse.tests", "documentation": ["__init__.py\n(c) Will Roberts  18 February, 2015\n\npytimeparse.tests module", "!/usr/bin/env python", "-*- coding: utf-8 -*-"], "functions": [], "variables": [], "classes": [], "exports": []}, {"name": "pytimeparse", "documentation": ["__init__.py\n(c) Will Roberts <wildwilhelm@gmail.com>   1 February, 2014\n\n`timeparse` module.", "!/usr/bin/env python", "-*- coding: utf-8 -*-"], "functions": [], "variables": [{"name": "pytimeparse.__version__", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "pytimeparse.__version__", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "pytimeparse.__version__", "type": null, "documentation": []}], "classes": [], "exports": [{"name": "pytimeparse.absolute_import", "xref": {"fqname": "__future__.absolute_import", "project": null}}, {"name": "pytimeparse.open", "xref": {"fqname": "codecs.open", "project": null}}, {"name": "pytimeparse.parse", "xref": {"fqname": "pytimeparse.timeparse.timeparse", "project": null}}, {"name": "pytimeparse.path", "xref": {"fqname": "os.path", "project": null}}]}, {"name": "pytimeparse.timeparse", "documentation": ["timeparse.py\n(c) Will Roberts <wildwilhelm@gmail.com>  1 February, 2014\n\nImplements a single function, `timeparse`, which can parse various\nkinds of time expressions.", "!/usr/bin/env python", "-*- coding: utf-8 -*-"], "functions": [{"name": "pytimeparse.timeparse._interpret_as_minutes", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "sval", "type": null, "default": null}, {"name": "mdict", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": ["Times like \"1:22\" are ambiguous; do they represent minutes and seconds\nor hours and minutes?  By default, timeparse assumes the latter.  Call\nthis function after parsing out a dictionary to change that assumption.\n\n```pycon\n>>> import pprint\n>>> pprint.pprint(_interpret_as_minutes('1:24', {'secs': '24', 'mins': '1'}))\n{'hours': '1', 'mins': '24'}\n```\n"]}, {"name": "pytimeparse.timeparse.timeparse", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "sval", "type": null, "default": null}, {"name": "granularity", "type": null, "default": "..."}], "returns": null, "documentation": ["Parse a time expression, returning it as a number of seconds.  If\npossible, the return value will be an `int`; if this is not\npossible, the return will be a `float`.  Returns `None` if a time\nexpression cannot be parsed from the given string.\n\nArguments:\n\\- `sval`: the string value to parse\n\n```pycon\n>>> timeparse('1:24')\n84\n>>> timeparse(':22')\n22\n>>> timeparse('1 minute, 24 secs')\n84\n>>> timeparse('1m24s')\n84\n>>> timeparse('1.2 minutes')\n72\n>>> timeparse('1.2 seconds')\n1.2\n```\n\nTime expressions can be signed.\n\n```pycon\n>>> timeparse('- 1 minute')\n-60\n>>> timeparse('+ 1 minute')\n60\n```\n\nIf granularity is specified as `minutes`, then ambiguous digits following\na colon will be interpreted as minutes; otherwise they are considered seconds.\n\n```pycon\n>>> timeparse('1:30')\n90\n>>> timeparse('1:30', granularity='minutes')\n5400\n```\n"]}], "variables": [{"name": "pytimeparse.timeparse.SIGN", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "pytimeparse.timeparse.WEEKS", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "pytimeparse.timeparse.DAYS", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "pytimeparse.timeparse.HOURS", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "pytimeparse.timeparse.MINS", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "pytimeparse.timeparse.SECS", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "pytimeparse.timeparse.SEPARATORS", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "pytimeparse.timeparse.SECCLOCK", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "pytimeparse.timeparse.MINCLOCK", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "pytimeparse.timeparse.HOURCLOCK", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "pytimeparse.timeparse.DAYCLOCK", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "pytimeparse.timeparse.OPT", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "pytimeparse.timeparse.OPTSEP", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "pytimeparse.timeparse.TIMEFORMATS", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "pytimeparse.timeparse.COMPILED_SIGN", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "pytimeparse.timeparse.COMPILED_TIMEFORMATS", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "pytimeparse.timeparse.MULTIPLIERS", "type": null, "documentation": []}], "classes": [], "exports": []}, {"name": "pytimeparse.tests.testtimeparse", "documentation": ["testtimeparse.py\n(c) Will Roberts <wildwilhelm@gmail.com>  1 February, 2014\n\nUnit tests for the `timeparse` module.", "!/usr/bin/env python", "-*- coding: utf-8 -*-"], "functions": [